 Its reasons are as follows: Preferences and dislikes extracted from my self-introduction: I prefer CDs with big, anthemic hard‑rock energy—thick, distorted guitar tones, stadium‑ready arrangements, polished, punchy production with forward drums and bass, layered backing vocals, and memorable, singalong choruses. I value greatest‑hits style compilations or tightly mastered rock albums that deliver immediate, replayable impact and work well in cars or social listening. I dislike releases that are mellow, lo‑fi, overly niche/archival, or that prioritize subtle tonal nuance over punch and polish.
Why High Voltage wins: High Voltage delivers the core elements I care about—guitar‑forward, distorted riffs and a tight, punchy rhythm section that produce immediate, replayable impact. The record’s blues‑based but energetic riffing and gritty, forward vocals create the kind of anthemic, singalong feel and stadium‑ready momentum I look for. The description notes robust mastering and steady, album‑oriented sequencing that preserve a cohesive, live‑feel grit—qualities that make it work well in solo driving or social listening and align with my desire for albums that hit hard and repeatedly. While it’s rawer than the most polished AOR productions, its forward drums/bass and guitar energy map closely to my preference for punch and replayability.
Why I reject Sleeping With The Past Remastered: Although it’s categorized as Classic Rock/AOR and a remaster may improve clarity, that style generally emphasizes keyboards, vocal‑forward arrangements and mid‑tempo AOR songwriting rather than the thick, distorted, stadium‑ready hard‑rock guitar tone and punchy, forward low end I prioritize. The album format and AOR aesthetic typically deliver a smoother, more adult‑contemporary soundscape rather than the big, gritty hard‑rock energy, singalong guitar choruses, and immediate punch I prefer. In short, Sleeping With The Past is less aligned with my specific appetite for heavy, distorted guitar drive and stadium‑style rock impact, so High Voltage is the better match.

